Genetic anticipation

#2020BSQ-JUL/Q40
Source
Refers to the appearance of signs and symptoms of a disease progressively earlier and earlier in successive generations.
Typical of diseases caused by a trinucleotide repeat.
These are sequences of 3 nucleotides which repeat. The number of repeats can increase from one generation to the next, making the DNA more and more unstable. Accumulation of these repeats is called trinucleotide repeat expansion.
Examples:

  1. Huntington's chorea
  2. Fragile X - the commonest form of autism of known cause.
  3. Myotonic dystrophy
  4. Spinocerebellar ataxia type 1
  5. [[General medicine 6-Neurology#Muscular dystrophies and myotonia|Spinal Muscular atrophy]] and bulbar muscular atrophy
  6. FRAXE mental retardation

Patterns of inheritance

Inheritance Pattern Characteristics Disease Examples
Autosomal Dominant Each affected person usually has an affected parent; occurs in every generation Huntingtons disease, neurofibromatosis, achondroplasia, familial hypercholesterolemia
Autosomal Recessive Both parents of an affected person are carriers; not typically seen in every generation Tay-Sachs disease, sickle cell anemia, cystic fibrosis, phenylketonuria (PKU)
X-linked Dominant Females are more frequently affected because all daughters and no sons of an affected man will be affected; can have affected males and females in same generation if the mother is affected Hypophatemic rickets (vitamin Dresistant rickets), ornithine transcarbamylase deficiency
X-linked Recessive Males are more frequently affected; affected males often present in each generation Hemophilia A, Duchenne muscular dystrophy
Mitochondrial Can affect both males and females, but only passed on by females because all mitochondria of all children come from the mother; can appear in every generation Lebers hereditary optic neuropathy, Kearns-Sayre syndrome

[!WARNING] Leishmaniasis is a notifiable disease in Sri Lanka as of 2008

Leishmaniasis in Sri Lanka

[!TIP] Leishmaniasis in Sri Lanka
DCOSL -> Donovani, cutaneous, in Sri Lanka

Source

In SL, leishmaniasis is reported mainly in Anuradphapura, polonnaruwa, hambantota and Matara. The disease was began spreading locally in the 1990s. Incidence has been increasing rapidly in the past decade.

Sri lanka is endemic for Leishmaniasis caused by Leishmania donovani.

In SL, Leishmania donovani (usually associated with visceral leshmaniasis (VL)) is causes cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL). This is termed dermotropism. However, it can case VL as well.
Phelbotomus argentipes is the main vector in SL although others are also present.
In SL, Leishmania incidence is seasonal.

Leishmaniasis has a wide spectrum of disease.

Diffuse cutaneous

Diffuse cutaneous leishmaniasis is a rare syndrome that occurs mainly in the setting of L.L. aethiopica, L.L. mexicana, and L.L. amazonensis infection.
It begins as a localized lesion that does not ulcerate; rather, amastigotes disseminate to macrophages in other areas of the skin. People who develop DCL usually have a defect in cell mediated immunity.

Musocal leishmaniasis

AKA espundia.
Mainly occurs in the 'new world'. (i.e North and south America).
So the causative parasites are L brazilliensis, guyanensis, panamensis, amazonensis,

aka Kala-azar (Hindi: black fever)

  • Main reservoir in Asia is dogs and foxes.
  • Untreated, the disease will progress to cause pancytopaenia and immunosuppresion leading to death in a year by superadded bacterial infection.
  • Diagnosis: Identification of the organisms in aspirate of bone marrow or liver or spleen.
  • Treatment: pentavalent antimony salts (Sodium stibogluconate / melumine antimoniate) OR IV amphotericin B and IM paromomycin. Some patients develop post kalar-azar dermal leishmaniasis.

Post kala-azar dermal leishmaniasis (PKDL)

  • Associated with Leishmania donovani.
  • A chronic skin rash which occurs after treatment of PKDL
  • Mimics leprosy in appearance but there is not sensory loss.
  • Perioral region is the earliest affected.
  • Median time to onset is about 6 months to 2 years after treatment.

Parietal lobe dysfunction features

#2020BSQ-JUL/Q56
The parietal lobe syndrome consists of

  1. constructional apraxia,
  2. visuospatial agnosia,
  3. topographical disorientation (getting lost, inability to learn new routes),
  4. visual inattention and
  5. cortical sensory loss, when objects can be felt but not fully interpreted or discriminated.

(Tay-sach's)
A #autosomal-Recessive defect in hexosaminidase which causes accumulation of lipids within cells. Particularly affects CNS neurons. Affected children develop normally until about 6 months of age and then show cognitive decline with loss of milestones, dementia, blindness and cherry red spots in the eyes.

Pathogenesis:
Urate is a product of purine metabolism.
It is eliminated by the kidney and this is regulated by resorptive proteins.

[!INFO] Note the drugs!
Thiazides and low dose aspirin can increase urate levels.

Decreased GFR (like in CKD) decreases urate elimination -> predisposes to gout.

  • Allopurinol is NOT used to treat flares.

  • Allopurinol:

    • #2020BSQ-JUL/Q44
    • Xanthine oxidase inhibitor -> rapidly lowers urate levels.
    • Only when attacks are frequent and problematic or if there is associated renal impairment. Side effects : GI disturbances, blood dyscrasias and rashes.
    • Always start under cover of NSAIDS or colchicine for a few weeks.

  • Febuxostat:

    • Non purine analog that inhibits xanthine oxidase.
    • As effective as allopurinol but overall associated with higher all cause mortality!
    • A pegylated recombinant uricase which very effectively lowers serum uric acid. Reserved for severe gout. Given IV.
